claims:
Claims WHAT IS CLAIMED IS: 1. A computer-implemented method of determining routes in geographic areas, comprising obtaining, by one or more computing devices, data indicative of a request for a route from an origin to a destination, wherein the one or more computing devices comprise one or more processors; accessing, by the one or more computing devices, first graph data modeling a travel segment network for a first geographic region; accessing, by the one or more computing devices, second graph data modeling a travel segment network for a second geographic region; identifying, by the one or more computing devices, a shortest path from the first graph data and the second graph data by visiting one or more nodes associated with boundary segments in the first graph data and the second graph data, the nodes associated with boundary segments being preserved in the graph data based at least in part on a reach value associated with each boundary segment; determining, by the one or more computing devices, a route from the origin to the destination based at least in part on the shortest path. 2. The computer-implemented method of claim 1 , wherein the shortest path is determined using a bi-directional contraction hierarchies search. 3. The computer-implemented method of claim 1, wherein the first graph data is associated with a different data version than the second graph data. 4. The computer-implemented method of claim 1, wherein the first graph data comprises first full graph data for a first base area of the first geographic region and one or more contraction cores for a first padding area of the first geographic region, each of the one or more contraction cores for the first padding area being generated based at least in part on a reach level associated with the contraction core. 5. The computer-implemented method of claim 4, wherein the second graph data comprises second full graph data for a second base area of the second geographic region and one or more contraction cores for a second padding area of the second geographic region, each of the one or more contraction cores for the second padding area being generated based at least in part on a reach level associated with the contraction core. 6. The computer-implemented method of claim 1, wherein the method further comprises accessing, by one or more computing devices, a sparse graph, the sparse graph associated with a reach level greater than or equal to a reach level threshold. 7. The computer-implemented method of claim 6, wherein the sparse graph models a highway network. 8. The computer-implemented method of claim 6, wherein the method comprises stitching, by the one or more computing devices, a boundary segment of the contraction core of the first padding area to the sparse graph. 9. The computer-implemented method of claim 6, wherein the method comprises stitching a boundary segment of the contraction core of the second padding area to the sparse graph. 10. The computer-implemented method of claim 5, wherein the first padding area of the first geographic region overlaps at least a portion of the second padding area of the second geographic region. 11. The computer-implemented method of claim 10, wherein the method comprises: determining, by the one or more computing devices, a seam between the first geographic region and the second geographic region; and stitching, by the one or more computing device, a boundary segment associated with one or more contraction cores for the first padding area with a boundary segment associated with one or more contraction cores for the second padding area at a boundary associated with the seam. 12. The computer-implemented method of claim 1, wherein the first graph data comprises a plurality of tile data objects configured in a tile data structure, the tile data structure comprising a base level and one or more hierarchical levels, each hierarchical level comprising tile data objects having graph data associated with a contraction core corresponding to the hierarchical level. 13. The computer-implemented method of claim 12, wherein the first geographic region comprises a plurality of cells in the first base region, for each cell in the first base region, the first graph data comprises a base tile data object associated with the base level in the tile data structure and a tile data object associated with each hierarchical level in the tile data structure. 14. The computer-implemented method of claim 12, wherein the first geographic area comprises a plurality of cells in the first padding area, for each cell in the first padding area, the first graph data includes tile data objects for each hierarchical level corresponding to a level greater than or equal to the level associated with the first padding area. 15. The computer-implemented method of claim 1, wherein the boundary segments are associated with one or more contraction cores generated from uncontracted graph data using a contraction hierarchies process, the contraction hierarchies process comprising: accessing, by the one or more computing devices, an uncontracted segment network graph; and progressively contracting, by the one or more computing devices, the uncontracted segment network graph for a plurality of contraction phases, each contraction phase being implemented based at least in part on a reach level associated with the contraction phase; wherein each contraction phase comprises marking a node associated with a boundary segment having a reach value greater than or equal to the reach level associated with the contraction phase as incontractible for the contraction phase. 16. A computing system, comprising: one or more processors; one or more memory devices, the one or more memory devices storing computer-readable instructions that when executed by the one or more memory devices cause the one or more memory devices to perform operations, the operations comprising: accessing uncontracted graph data modeling a travel segment network; progressively contracting the uncontracted graph data for a plurality of contraction phases to generate a plurality of contraction cores corresponding to a plurality of different reach levels, each contraction phase being implemented based at least in part on a reach value associated with the reach level corresponding to the contraction phase; generating a plurality of base tile data objects for the full graph data; generating a plurality of first tile data objects corresponding to a first contraction core of the plurality of contraction cores, the first contraction core associated with a first reach value; and 

 generating a plurality of second tile data objects corresponding to a second contraction core of the plurality of contractions cores, the second contraction core associated with a second reach value; wherein the second reach value is greater than the first reach value. 17. The computing system of claim 16, wherein each contraction phase comprises marking a node associated with a boundary segment having a reach value greater than or equal to the reach value associated with the contraction phase as incontractible for the contraction phase. 18. One or more tangible, non-transitory computer-readable media storing computer-readable instructions that when executed by one or more processors cause the one or more processors to perform operations, the operations comprising: accessing first graph data associated with a first geographic region having a first base area, a first inner padding ring, and a first outer padding ring, wherein the first inner padding ring is associated with a first reach level and the first outer padding ring is associated with a second reach level, the second reach level being greater than the first reach level, the first graph data comprising first full graph data for each of a plurality of cells in the first base area, the first graph data further comprising first contracted graph data associated with the first reach level for each of a plurality of cells in the first inner padding ring, the first graph data further comprising second contracted graph data associated with the second reach level for each of a plurality of cells in the first outer padding ring; accessing second graph data associated with a second geographic region having a second base area, a second inner padding ring, and a second outer padding ring, wherein the second inner padding ring is associated with the first reach level and the second outer padding ring is associated with the second reach level, the second graph data comprising second full graph data for each of a plurality of cells in the second base area, the second graph data further comprising third contracted graph data associated with the first reach level for each of a plurality of cells in the second inner padding ring, the second graph data further comprising fourth contracted graph data associated with the second reach level for each of a plurality of cells in the second outer padding ring; determining, by the one or more computing devices, a seam between the first geographic region and the second geographic region; 

 stitching the first contracted graph data associated with the first inner padding ring to the third contracted graph data associated with the second inner padding ring at a boundary associated with the seam to generate a stitched graph model; stitching the second contracted graph data associated with the first outer padding ring to the fourth contracted graph data associated with the second outer padding ring at a boundary associated with the seam to generate the stitched graph model; and determining a route from an origin in the first geographic region to a destination in the second geographic region based at least in part on the stitched graph model using a contraction hierarchies search algorithm. 19. The one or more tangible, non-transitory computer-readable media of claim 18, wherein the first graph data and the second graph data are accessed without network connectivity. 20. The one or more tangible, non-transitory computer-readable media of claim 19, wherein the first graph data is associated with a different data version than the second graph data.
